title-group.article-title: Computational Investigations of the Impact Resistance of Aluminum–Epoxy–Laminated Composites

article-meta.aff: Department of Materials Science and Engineering, Saveh Branch, Islamic Azad University, Saveh, Iran

author-notes.corresp: *Author to whom correspondence should be addressed. E-mail: alinazari84@aut.ac.ir

abstract.p: In this article, Charpy impact resistance of aluminum–epoxy–laminated composites in both crack divider and crack arrester configurations has been investigated. In both configurations, an analytical investigation has been carried out to evaluate the effects of layer thickness on impact resistance of the specimens. A model based on gene expression programming for predicting impact resistance of the specimens has been presented. To build the model, training and testing were conducted using experimental results from 126 specimens produced of two basic composites. The used data as inputs of gene expression programming models are arranged in a format of seven parameters that cover the thickness of layers, the number of layers, the adhesive type, the crack tip configuration, the content of SiC particles, the content of methacrylated butadiene–styrene particles, and the number of test trials. According to these input parameters, in the gene expression programming model, the impact resistance of each specimen was predicted. The training and testing results in the gene expression programming model have shown a strong potential for predicting impact resistance of aluminum–epoxy–laminated composites.

sec.title: INTRODUCTION
sec.p: Aluminum laminates are well suited to aerospace applications as they exhibit higher impact strengths compared to most monolithic and other composite materials (Vaziri et al., 1996; Liu et al., 2000). Most investigations in this field, however, are focused on the behavior of laminates under static loading (Lu et al., 1991; Xiao and Abbaschian, 1992; Howard et al., 1998), while only a limited amount of work has been carried on laminates subjected to impact loading (Ellis and Lewandowski, 1994; McLelland et al., 1999; Tekyeh-Marouf et al., 2004). The original works in this field are those of Kaufman (1967) and Goolsby (1978), who compared the static fracture toughness of monolithic aluminum with that of laminates. Those researchers reported the superior toughness of the laminates compared to that of the monolithic aluminum (Al). Manoharan et al. (1990) investigated the fracture behavior of a two-layer laminated structure, which consisted of an unreinforced Al layer and a discontinuously reinforced aluminum (DRA) layer. They reported a 10% increase in the initiation and 250% increase in the propagation fracture toughness in a double-layer aluminum/DRA compared to a monolayer DRA.

These studies illustrate the importance of the number of layers in static performance of the laminates; however, there has been no systematic effort in those investigations to keep the laminate thickness constant. This is important because the thickness of the specimen will significantly affect the amount of energy absorbed during impact.

There are several works on properties of laminated composites investigating their different mechanical properties by numerical, analytical, and computational methods (Haj-Ali, 2009; Lubineau, 2010). The few studies that have been carried out laminated composites include a study of impact resistance of Al/DRA composites (Ellis and Lewandowski, 1994; McLelland et al., 1999), and one involving Al/epoxy laminates (Laliberte et al., 2000). Ellis and Lewandowski (1994) noticed an enhancement of the impact resistance by increasing the Al layer thickness in a bi-layer Al/DRA composite, while McLelland et al. (1999) reported a modest increase in impact resistanceby increasing the number of layers in a multilayer Al/DRA composite. Laliberte et al. (2000) found an optimum number of layers in their Al/epoxy multilayer specimens subjected to impact loading.

Genetic programming (GP) has begun to arise for the explicit formulation of the properties and the performances of engineering materials recently (Cevik and Sonebi, 2008, 2009). GP offers many advantages as compared to classical regression techniques. Regression techniques are often based onpredefined functions where regression analyses of these functions are later performed. On the other hand, in the case of GP approach, there is no predefined function to be considered. In this sense, GP can be accepted to be superior to regression techniques and neural networks. GP has proven to be an effective tool to model and obtain explicit formulations of experimental studies including multivariate parameters where there are no existing analytical models (Cevik and Sonebi, 2008, 2009).

The aim of this study is to predict impact resistance of aluminum–epoxy-laminated composites in both crack divider and crack arrester configurations by GEP. Totally, 126 data of Charpy impact tests in different conditions were collected, trained, and tested by means of GEP. The obtained results have been compared by experimental ones to evaluate the software power for predicting the impact resistance of aluminum–epoxy–laminated composites.

sec.title: EXPERIMENTAL PROCEDURE
sec.p: A commercially pure Al plate was used as the base material and a two-part epoxy polymer, including resin and curing agent, was incorporated as the adhesive material. The adhesive was modified using core–shell rubber particles and silicon carbide particles (SiC). Core–shell rubber particles comprised a methacrylated butadiene–styrene (MBS) copolymer with a nominal diameter of less than 350 nm.

The average particle size of the utilized SiC particles was 10 µm. The additive content was varied from 5 to 15 vol.%. The designation for each formulation used in this study is outlined in Table 1. Table 1.

Three types of laminates, including 2-, 5-, and 10-layer specimens, along with the monolithic specimen, were considered for studying the influence of laminate architecture on the impact resistance. A 10-mm thick aluminum bar was used to make the monolithic specimen. The same material was hot rolled down to different thicknesses for preparation of the laminates. The layer thicknesses in 2-, 5-, and 10-layer specimens were 5, 2 and 1 mm, respectively. The thickness of the layers was selected such that the total aluminum thickness in each laminate was 10 mm and all layers in each laminate had the same thickness. All aluminum bars were solution heat treated at 400°C followed by a cold water quench.

Impact specimens were notched perpendicular to the interface of the layers using a diamond saw in both crack divider (Figure 1(a)) and crack arrester (Figure 1(b)) configurations. The notches were 2 mm deep. Figure 1.
Schematic representation of Charpy impact specimens’ preparation in (a) crack divider, (b) crack arrester configurations, and (c) dimensions of Charpy impact specimen.

The impact behavior of laminated composites was evaluated using Charpy impact test using standard-sized specimens according to the ASTM E23 (ASTM, 2001). Figure 1(c) shows the impact specimens investigated in this study. Charpy impact testing was conducted on a pendulum impact tester using a maximum capacity of 300 J. Three samples of each material were examined.

As seen in Table 2, all laminated composites possess significantly higher impact energies compared to the monolithic aluminum specimen (185 ± 13 kJ/m2). As seen, the laminates absorbed higher energy during the fracture under impact loading than that of the monolithic specimen. This observation can be attributed to the influence of interfaces introduced in the laminates. The triaxial stress field ahead of the crack tips may cause debonding at the up front interface(s). This in turn reduces the crack driving force due to the need for crack renucleation in the next layer(s) (Cao and Evans, 1991; He et al., 1993). It may also cause a possible transition from plane strain to plane stress that results in further plastic deformation and thus, extra energy absorption in the aluminum layers (Osman and Lewandowski, 1994; Pandey et al., 2001). In either case, the impact resistance is improved.

sec.title: GENETIC PROGRAMMING
sec.p:
GP proposed by Koza is an extension to genetic algorithms. Koza defines GP as a domain-independent problem-solving approach in which computer programs are evolved to solve, or approximately solve, problems based on the Darwinian principle of reproduction and survival of the fittest and analogs of naturally occurring genetic operations such as crossover and mutation. GP reproduces computer programs to solve problems by executing the steps in Figure 2. This figure is a flowchart showing the executional steps of a run of GP. The flowchart demonstrates the genetic operations in addition to the architecture chancing operations. Also, it demonstrates a two-offspring version of the crossover operation. Figure 2.
GP flowchart (He et al., 1993).

Gene expression programming (GEP) software used in this study is an extension to GEP that evolves computer programs of different sizes and shapes encoded in linear chromosomes of fixed length. The chromosomes are composed of multiple genes, each gene encoding a smaller sub-program. Furthermore, the structural and functional organization of the linear chromosomes allows the unconstrained operation of important genetic operators such as mutation, transposition, and recombination (Rosenblatt, 1962; Rumelhart et al., 1986; Liu et al., 2002). The two main parameters in GEP are the chromosomes and expression trees (ETs) (Rosenblatt, 1962; Rumelhart et al., 1986; Liu et al., 2002). Two languages are utilized in GEP: the language of the genes and the language of ETs. A significant advantage of GEP is that it enables us to infer exactly the phenotype given the sequence of a gene and vice versa, which is termed as Karva language.

For each problem, the type of linking function, as well as the number of genes and the length of each gene, are a priori chosen for each problem. While attempting to solve a problem, one can always start by using a single-gene chromosome and then proceed by increasing the length of the head. If it becomes very large, one can increase the number of genes and obviously choose a function to link the sub-ETs. One can start with addition for algebraic expressions or for Boolean expressions, but in some cases, another linking function might be more appropriate (like multiplication or IF, for instance). The idea, of course, is to find a good solution, and GEP provides the means of finding one very efficiently (Rosenblatt, 1962).

sec.title: GEP Structure and Parameters
sec.p:
In this study, as seen in Figures 3 and 4, the ETs of two different GEP approach models, namely GEP-I and GEP-II, were constructed for CVN values. In Figures 3 and 4, d0, d1, d2, d3, d4, d5, and d6, representing the values for input layers, were the thickness of layers (T), the number of layers (N), the adhesive type (A), the crack tip configuration (C), the content of SiC particles (S), the content of MBS particles (M), and the number of test trial (NT), respectively. In the GEP-I and GEP-II, as the number of genes used are 3 and 4 (Sub-ETs), and linking functions used are addition and multiplication, respectively. In training and testing of the GEP-I and GEP-II approach models constituted with two different Sub-ETs and linking function T, N, A, C, S, M, and NT are used as input data and CVN as independent output data. Among 126 experimental sets, 103 sets were randomly chosen as a training set for the GEP-I and GEPII modeling and the remaining 23 sets were used as testing the generalization capacity of the proposed models. For this problem, first, the fitness, fi, of an individual program, i, is measured by: (17) where M is the range of selection, C(i, j) the value returned by the individual chromosome i for fitness case j (out of Ct fitness cases), and Tj the target value for fitness case j. If |C(i, j) - Tj| (the precision) is less than or equal to 0.01, then the precision is equal to zero, and fi = fmax = CtM. In this case, M = 100 was use; therefore, fmax = 1000. The advantage of this kind of fitness functions is that the system can find the optimal solution by itself (Hopfield et al., 1982; Anderson et al., 1983).

Afterward, the set of terminals T and the set of functions F to create the chromosomes are preferred, namely, T = {T, N, A, C, S, M, NT}, four basic arithmetic operators (+, −, ×, /), and some basic mathematical functions (Sqrt, x3) were used.

Another major step is to choose the chromosomal tree, i.e., the length of the head and the number of genes. The GEP-I and GEP-II approach models initially used single gene and two lengths of heads, and increased the number of genes and heads, one after another during each run, and monitored the training and testing sets performance of each model. In this study, for the GEP-I and GEP-II approach models observed the number of genes as 3 and 4, and lengths of heads as 10 and 12, respectively. In addition, for the GEP-I and GEP-II approach models, we determined the linking functions multiplication and addition, respectively.

Finally, a combination of all genetic operators (mutation, transposition, and crossover) was utilized as set of genetic operators. Parameters of the training of the GEP-I and GEP-II approach models are given in Table 3. For the GEP-I and GEP-II approach models, chromosomes 30 and 40 were observed to be the best of generation individuals predicting CVN. sec.title: PREDICTED RESULTS AND DISCUSSION
sec.p: In this study, the error arising during the training and testing in GEP-I and GEP-II models can be expressed as absolute fraction of variance (R2), calculated by Equation (19) (Topcu and Sarıdemir, 2008): (19) where t is the target value, o the output value, and p the pattern.

The performance of the GEP-I and GEP-II models is shown in Figure 6. The best value of R2 is 97.73% for training set in the GEP-II model. The minimum values of R2 are 91.95% for testing set in the GEP-I model. All R2 values show that the proposed GEP-I and GEP-II models are suitable and can predict CVN values very close to the experimental values.

list-item.p: The impact resistance of the aluminum–epoxy–laminated composites in both crack divider and crack arrester configurations was higher than that of monolithic aluminum specimen.
In both crack divider and crack arrester configurations, the impact resistance of the specimens depended on the number of layers together with the bonding strength of the utilized adhesive.
GEP can be an alternative approach for the evaluation of the effect of layer’s number and bonding strength on CVN values of laminated composites.
Comparison between GEP in terms of R2 showed that GEP models are capable of predicting suitable results for CVN values.
